Orientation in Guatemala2 Weeks
Orientation will help you prepare for the program ahead.Orientation in Guatemala2 Weeks
Orientation will help you prepare for the program ahead. This includes:
Cultural sensitivity training to learn to communicate across language barriers and effectively immerse yourself in a new culture
Health & safety training 
Team building exercises to unite your group
Begin observing how healthy communities are built
Explore the gorgeous coast of Guatemala, with loads of sea life sightings  




 

 












 
 
Watch Student Media 






 Unit 1: Food & Sustainability - Guatemala7 Weeks
It takes holistic knowledge and experience to resolve global issues. This program explores how public health is the foundation for development, how education can truly empower, and how sustainable environmental practices can protect food supplies.Unit 1: Food & Sustainability - Guatemala7 Weeks
It takes holistic knowledge and experience to resolve global issues. This program explores how public health is the foundation for development, how education can truly empower, and how sustainable environmental practices can protect food supplies.
This unit includes:

Waste Management in Guatemala City - Students work alongside local organizations working to protect inhabitants from the harmful effects of pollution and waste.
Food Sustainability in Tecpán – Students work on small plots with farming families seeking to bring healthy and sustainable practices to their region.
 










 Enrichment Trip: Mayan Ruins & Volcanoes1 Week
Guatemala is rich with historical and natural sites to explore, from the 37 volcanoes that are dotted around the country to the majestic Mayan ruins in Tikal.
Mayan Ruins in Tikal – Travel north to the ancient temples and pathways of Tikal, the best preserved Mayan city in Guatemala (and one of the most impressive in the world).
Pacaya Volcano - Breathtaking views all around as you hike the rugged terrain of this massive volcano. Your sweet reward at the top: toasting marshmallows in the active lava. 
 
Enrichment Trip: Mayan Ruins & Volcanoes1 Week
Guatemala is rich with historical and natural sites to explore, from the 37 volcanoes that are dotted around the country to the majestic Mayan ruins in Tikal. 




 

 












 
 
Watch Student Media 






 Unit 2: Education that Empowers - India7 Weeks
Education is the keystone of development. You’ll explore how education empowers communities to improve health, support gender equity, and foster justice. You’ll work in education centers for women and children in some of the poorest parts of Delhi and Dharamsala. You’ll visit the breathtaking Taj Mahal and immerse your senses in the rich smells, sounds, and colors of markets and festivals.Unit 2: Education that Empowers -- India7 Weeks
Education is the keystone of development. You’ll explore how education empowers communities to improve health, support gender equity, and foster justice. You’ll work in education centers for women and children in some of the poorest parts of Delhi and Dharamsala. You’ll visit the breathtaking Taj Mahal and immerse your senses in the rich smells, sounds, and colors of markets and festivals.
This unit includes:
Education for Women & Children in Dharamsala – Students work in local schools and children’s clubs to support community education initiatives.
Education in New Delhi – Students work with community education initiatives ranging from preschools to providing English and computer skills to young adults.
 










 Enrichment Trip: Temples of Angkor Wat1 Week
Cambodia offers students the stark contrast of getting to see both some of the world's most spiritual sites and some of the places where histories largest crimes against humanity occurred.
Siem Reap & Angkor Wat - Students will visit the magnificent Angkor Wat, the world’s largest religious monument. See the “Temple City” at dawn to witness the spectacular sunrise over the temples.
Phnom Penh & The Killing Fields – Students visit Cambodia's capital to reflect on the powerful landmarks related to the Cambodian Genocide, learn how this part of the country’s history came to be, and how it affects communities today.
 
 
Enrichment Trip: Temples of Angkor Wat1 Week
Cambodia offers students the stark contrast of getting to see both some of the world's most spiritual sites and some of the places where histories largest crimes against humanity occurred.  




 

 












 
 
Watch Student Media 






 Unit 3: Public Health - Ghana7 Weeks
Effective Public Health systems require education, sanitation infrastructure, and access to medical services. You’ll work in the beautiful Volta region alongside local professionals to improve community health conditions while reflecting on how resources, culture, and social structures affect these efforts. Unit 3: Public Health -- Ghana7 Weeks
Effective Public Health systems require education, sanitation infrastructure, and access to medical services. You’ll work in the beautiful Volta region alongside local professionals to improve community health conditions while reflecting on how resources, culture, and social structures affect these efforts.
This unit includes:
Working in Clinics - In partnership with the government health department, students are placed in multiple community clinics to support nurses and provide administrative support.
Public Health Outreach – Students partner with community health workers to assist in the creation of materials for outreach workshops around hygiene, maternal health, and malaria prevention. 










 Enrichment Trip: Desert Nomads & Culture1 Week
Morocco offers a rich cultural history and present. You'll explore sacred sites for the Muslims of the nation, and see and smell the incredible markets of the towns and cities. Cap it with a camel trek through the desert, and it's an amazing adventure! 
 
Enrichment Trip: Desert Nomads & Culture1 Week
Morocco offers a rich cultural history and present. You'll explore sacred sites for the Muslims of the nation, and see and smell the incredible markets of the towns and cities. Cap it with a camel trek through the desert, and it's an amazing adventure! 




 

 












 
 







 Culmination: Washington, D.C.3 Weeks
There is no city in the world with more people working to create change than Washington, DC. You’ll meet representatives from the World Bank, UN Foundation, and leading international organizations to discuss how we can create more empowered and sustainable communities. In addition, you will meet with actual representatives in Congress to share what you've learned and express your opinions.
In the final days, students will work to create a final project – a presentation culminating their experiences. At the end, we will host a graduation for you and your families to attend to celebrate your year's accomplishments.Culmination: Washington, D.C.3 Weeks
There is no city in the world with more people working to create change than Washington, DC. You’ll meet representatives from the World Bank, UN Foundation, and leading international organizations to discuss how we can create more empowered and sustainable communities. In addition, you will meet with actual representatives in Congress to share what you've learned and express your opinions.
In the final days, students will work to create a final project – a presentation culminating their experiences. At the end, we will host a graduation for you and your families to attend to celebrate your year's accomplishments. 











 GLOBAL GAP YEAR PROGRAM REVIEWS





Shawn Childs
Global Gap Year 2010








“I felt much more prepared and invested in my college courses than many of my peers. TBB taught me to take an active role in my education and to be an advocate for myself. I was able to relate to the information on a much more practical, realistic level. I sought out classes that had a reputation for being more focused on student-involvement and steered away from larger, lecture style-courses. This is a bit of advice that I would pass on to anyone entering college as it’s by far the best way to feel comfortable with and fully understand the relevance of the information being taught, as well as becoming more confident in yourself.”



Janet Childs, Mother of Shawn
Global Gap Year 2010

“Shawn’s priorities in college are much more focused than most college freshmen’s. She met with advisors repeatedly to pinpoint the most efficient path to achieving her major and minors all within 3 1/2 years.”










































 





